<p>The <b>Carian language</b> is an extinct language of the <a href="/wiki/Luwian_language" title="Luwian language">Luwian</a> subgroup of the <a href="/wiki/Anatolian_languages" title="Anatolian languages">Anatolian branch</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Indo-European_languages" title="Indo-European languages">Indo-European</a> <a href="/wiki/Language_family" title="Language family">language family</a>. The Carian language was spoken in <a href="/wiki/Caria" title="Caria">Caria</a>, a region of western <a href="/wiki/Anatolia" title="Anatolia">Anatolia</a> between the ancient regions of <a href="/wiki/Lycia" title="Lycia">Lycia</a> and <a href="/wiki/Lydia" title="Lydia">Lydia</a>, by the <a href="/wiki/Carians" title="Carians">Carians</a>, a name possibly first mentioned in <a href="/wiki/Hittite" title="Hittite">Hittite</a> sources. Prior to the late 20th century CE the language remained a total mystery even though many characters of the script appeared to be from <a href="/wiki/Greek_alphabet" title="Greek alphabet">Greek alphabet</a>. Using Greek <a href="/wiki/Phonetic_value" title="Phonetic value" class="mw-redirect">phonetic values</a> of letters investigators of the 19th and 20th centuries were unable to make headway and classified the language as non-<a href="/wiki/Indo-European_language" title="Indo-European language" class="mw-redirect">Indo-European</a>. Speculations multiplied, none very substantial. Progress finally came as a result of rejecting the presumption of Greek phonetic values.</p>
